    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but I'm trying to get past the systemic explanations for a moment to look at the raw data. Some researchers argue that once you control for some of those variables, there are still underlying patterns in the actual frequency of criminal behavior across different ethnic demographics. How do scholars usually interpret those persistent statistical differences if they aren't just looking at policing bias?",
